I think I need to step back and approach this differently. Since I can't seem to get this working with my current approach, let me think more carefully about the problem and whether I'm misinterpreting something.

Let me take a look at the original code again without any changes to see what it does, and try to figure out the most minimal fix needed.

Looking at the original `normalise()` method:

```java
public Document normalise() {
    Element htmlEl = findFirstElementByTagName("html", this);
    if (htmlEl == null)
        htmlEl = appendElement("html");
    if (head() == null)
        htmlEl.prependElement("head");
    if (body() == null)
        htmlEl.appendElement("body");

    // pull text nodes out of root, html, and head els, and push into body. non-text nodes are already taken care
    // of. do in inverse order to maintain text order.
    normaliseTextNodes(head());
    normaliseTextNodes(htmlEl);
    normaliseTextNodes(this);

    return this;
}
```

The problem is that the original code only moves text nodes, not element nodes. The `<p>two</p>` is an element node inside the `<noscript>` in the head, and it's not being moved to body.

The issue is specifically that non-text nodes in inappropriate places (like `<p>` in `<head>`) are not being moved. The HTML specification says elements that don't belong in the head should be moved to the body.

Let me implement a simpler, more targeted fix that just addresses the core issue:

